  "reason_thou": "### 1. Understanding the Issue\n\nThe `gvn` pass is crashing with an
assertion failure: `!isa<IndirectBrInst>(TI) && \"Cannot split critical edge from
IndirectBrInst\"`. This assertion is in `SplitKnownCriticalEdge`, a utility function for
breaking critical edges. A critical edge is one that goes from a block with multiple
successors to a block with multiple predecessors. The utility function explicitly forbids
splitting edges that originate from an `indirectbr` instruction, as this is a complex and
generally unsupported operation.\n\nThe crash occurs because the GVN pass, during its
optimization process, incorrectly decides it needs to split a critical edge that starts from a
basic block terminated by an `indirectbr`.\n\n### 2. Analyzing `opt`'s Log and
Backtrace\n\nThe backtrace is the key to understanding the sequence of events:\n\n1.
`GVNPass::processFoldableCondBr(BI)`: GVN processes the `br i1 false, label %ibr, label %exit`
in the `entry` block. It correctly identifies that the condition is a constant (`false`),
meaning the branch will always go to `%exit`.\n2.  This makes the edge `entry -> %ibr` dead.
Since `%ibr` has no other predecessors, the entire `%ibr` block becomes dead.\n3.
`GVNPass::addDeadBlock(BB)`: GVN then calls `addDeadBlock` to handle the now-dead `%ibr`
block.\n4.  `GVNPass::splitCriticalEdges(From, To)`: Inside `addDeadBlock`, there's logic to
clean up the CFG. It iterates through the successors of the dead block (`%ibr`) and attempts
to split any critical edges. The edge `%ibr -> %exit` is identified as critical because `%ibr`
has multiple successors (even though they are the same block, `%exit`), and `%exit` has
multiple predecessors (`%entry` and `%ibr`).\n5.  `llvm::SplitCriticalEdge(...)`: This leads
to the call to split the edge, which ultimately hits the assertion because the terminator of
`%ibr` is an `indirectbr`.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe root cause lies in the
`addDeadBlock` function within `GVN.cpp`. This function is responsible for cleaning up after a
block is proven to be dead. Part of its cleanup involves splitting critical edges between the
dead block and its successors. The code snippet is:\n\n```cpp\n// GVN.cpp:addDeadBlock\nfor
(BasicBlock *Succ : successors(BB)) {\n  if (isCriticalEdge(BB, Succ))\n
splitCriticalEdges(BB, Succ);\n}\n```\n\nThis logic is flawed. While splitting critical edges
is often a good preparatory step for other optimizations, it is completely unnecessary for a
block that is *already dead*. A dead block and all its outgoing edges will be removed by a
subsequent dead code elimination (DCE) pass anyway. Attempting to \"clean up\" its edges is
redundant and, in this specific case, fatal, because it runs into the `indirectbr`
limitation.\n\nThe fix is straightforward: we should not attempt to split critical edges
originating from a block that GVN has just proven to be dead. The entire loop in
`addDeadBlock` that calls `splitCriticalEdges` should be removed.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit
Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to remove the problematic loop in `GVNPass::addDeadBlock`.\n\n*
**File**: `llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/GVN.cpp`\n*   **Edit**: Remove the lines that iterate
through successors of a dead block to split critical edges, and replace them with the correct
logic to just update PHI nodes.\n\nI will replace the following lines from
`llvm/lib/Transforms/Scalar/GVN.cpp` (lines 3309-3314):\n\n```cpp\n  // If the dead block has
any successors, then the edges from the\n  // dead block to the successor are dead.  If the
successor has any\n  // PHI nodes, update them to reflect this.  We do this here because\n  //
we need to update the PHI nodes before we run any other\n  // optimizations.\n  for
(BasicBlock *Succ : successors(BB)) {\n    if (isCriticalEdge(BB, Succ))\n
splitCriticalEdges(BB, Succ);\n    Succ->removePredecessor(BB);\n  }\n```\n\nwith:\n\n```cpp\n
// If the dead block has any successors, then the edges from the\n  // dead block to the
successor are dead.  If the successor has any\n  // PHI nodes, update them to reflect this.\n
for (BasicBlock *Succ : successors(BB))\n    Succ->removePredecessor(BB);\n```\n\n### 5.
Conclusion\n\nThe GVN pass was trying to be overly helpful by cleaning up critical edges from
a block it had just identified as dead. This cleanup is not only unnecessary (as the block is
slated for removal) but also buggy, as it doesn't account for terminators like `indirectbr`
that have restrictions on edge splitting. By removing this redundant cleanup logic from
`addDeadBlock`, we fix the crash and allow the pass to complete successfully. The subsequent
DCE pass will handle the removal of the dead block and its associated edges correctly.",
